from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

def calc_vif(X):

    # Calculating VIF
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["variables"] = X.columns
    vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]

    return(vif)
calc_vif(df[['Population','Adult Mortality','infant deaths','GDP','Schooling','percentage expenditure','Life expectancy ','Alcohol']])

Below is my attempt to calculate Hausman effect in Python, but I opted for Stata as met major difficulties here

import numpy.linalg as la from scipy import stats import numpy as np def hausman(fe, re): b = fe.params B = re.params v_b = fe.cov v_B = re.cov df = b[np.abs(b) < 1e8].size chi2 = np.dot((b - B).T, la.inv(v_b - v_B).dot(b - B))

pval = stats.chi2.sf(chi2, df)
return chi2, df, pval

hausman_results = hausman(fe_res, re_res) print('chi-Squared:' + str(hausman_results[0])) print('degrees of freedom:' + str(hausman_results[1])) print('p-Value:' + str(hausman_results[2]))

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

def calc_vif(X):

    # Calculating VIF
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["variables"] = X.columns
    vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]

    return(vif)
